Official solution: We can use Pascal's identity $ \binom{n-1}{k-1}+\binom{n-1}{k}=\binom{n}{k}$ to find $\binom{15}{9}$.

\begin{align*}
\binom{15}{8}+\binom{15}{9}&=\binom{16}{9} \rightarrow \\
6435+\binom{15}{9}&=11440 \rightarrow \\
\binom{15}{9}&=5005
\end{align*}

We can use the identity again to find $\binom{15}{10}$.

\begin{align*}
\binom{15}{9}+\binom{15}{10}&=\binom{16}{10} \rightarrow \\
5005+\binom{15}{10}&=8008 \rightarrow \\
\binom{15}{10}&=3003
\end{align*}

Therefore, $\binom{15}{10}=\boxed{3003}$.

Official solution: By Pascal's Rule, \begin{align*}
\binom{15}{7} &= \binom{14}{6} + \binom{14}{7} \\
\binom{15}{7} &= \binom{14}{14-6} + \binom{14}{7} \\
\binom{15}{7} &= \binom{14}{8} + \binom{14}{7} \\
\binom{15}{7} &= 3003 + 3432 \\
\binom{15}{7} &= \boxed{6435}
\end{align*}

Official solution: We can rewrite $2007^3$ as the cube of a binomial: \begin{align*}
2007^3 &= (2\cdot 10^3 + 7)^3\\
&= \binom{3}{0} (2\cdot 10^3)^3 + \cdots + \binom{3}{3} 7^3
\end{align*}

Only the first and last term of the binomial expansion affect the values of $F$ and $L$. The first term is equal to $8\cdot 10^9$, so $F = 8$. The last term is equal to 343, so $L = 3$. Therefore, $F + L = \boxed{11}$.

